As an autolisp-spec consumer, I want the built PDF's filename
to embed the spec's version number so that an installed or
downloaded copy is self-identifying — `0.8.2`, `0.9.0`,
`1.0.0`, … visible in the filename rather than determined
by mtime, file hash, or opening the PDF and reading the
title page.

Today the build produces

    autolisp-spec/documentation/autolisp-visual-lisp-specification-draft.pdf

regardless of which version of the spec was built. The
original autolisp-spec-paged-version issue (closed
2026-05-25, merge 98ca5d5) asked for

    autolisp-spec/build/autolisp-visual-lisp-specification-draft-${version}.pdf

— versioned filename, under build/ rather than alongside the
org source. The merge took the simpler convention
(`$(ORG_FILES:.org=.pdf)' in the Makefile, same dir as the
source, no version suffix), which left this naming wish
unmet.

The version is already in the source — line 5 of
autolisp-visual-lisp-specification-draft.org carries
`#+VERSION: 0.8.2', and the document body asserts at line
16 that "Any modification of this document must increment
its version number." A Make rule can extract that string
and use it.

Acceptance:

- `make documentation` (and the umbrella `make build')
  produces a PDF whose basename includes the version,
  e.g. `autolisp-visual-lisp-specification-draft-0.8.2.pdf'.
- The location may remain `documentation/' (alongside the
  org source) or move to `build/' — either is fine; pick
  whichever is more consistent with sibling subprojects.
  Document the choice in the Makefile header comment.
- `make install' installs the versioned PDF under
  $(PREFIX)/share/doc/autolisp-spec/ AND drops an
  unversioned symlink (or copy) next to it so consumers
  who don't want to hard-code a version can refer to
  `autolisp-visual-lisp-specification-draft.pdf'.
  The unversioned name is what existing tooling and
  bookmarks already use; keep it working.
- `make uninstall' removes both.
- The version string is extracted from the org source's
  `#+VERSION:' line at build time — not hard-coded in the
  Makefile — so bumping the spec's version in one place
  (the org file) propagates to the PDF filename without a
  second edit.

Out of scope:

- Versioning the other PDFs (autolisp-reference-notes,
  vendor-inventory-2026, specification-resolution-plan).
  Those documents don't carry a `#+VERSION:' line today
  and don't share the spec's release cadence; if a need
  arises, open a separate issue.
- Embedding the version into the HTML/Info builds. The
  HTML manual is browsed in-place from one rendered tree
  and doesn't need filename versioning; Info already
  ships under `autolisp-spec.info' with the version
  visible in the title page.
- Changing the source-file convention (`#+VERSION:').
  This issue consumes that field, doesn't redefine it.

Spawned from the autolisp-spec-paged-version close-out
audit: the PDF filename was the one unmet line item from
that issue's deliverable list, called out as worth either
fixing or accepting-as-deviation.
